post_text:
Skiatook Public Schools Parents, Staff, and Students.

The Oklahoma Department of Health COVID-19 Alert System has released the August 20, 2020 county risk levels. Osage County was listed at 42.59 cases per 100,000. This number equates to the Oklahoma State Department of Education risk level of Orange Level 2. However, the Osage County Health Department has notified us that 69.9% of the new cases were attributed to an institution within Osage County in which there is no risk of community spread. When the institution facility cases are removed from the population, Osage County is at an Orange Level 1 status.

Skiatook Public Schools was awarded a Hotspot Grant from the Oklahoma State Department of Education through COVID-19 relief funds to service 5% of our student population. During the 2020-21 school year, selected students who lack an internet connection in their home may utilize a hotspot for a portion of the school year at no cost to the student. Students will be required to return the hotspot at the end of the school year.

Please visit https://forms.gle/gwuhRzYTVwEHt3nX7 to access the request form. This application is due Friday, August 21, 2020.

post_text:
Skiatook Schools is seeking a Support Staff Specialist for the 2020-21 school year. This is a 12-month position in the Education Service Center. Job duties include, but are not limited to the following: Receptionist, Child Nutrition Clerk, assisting with Human Resources, Federal Programs Assistant, and other clerical duties. Candidate must have excellent people and computer skills

This job requires the ability to work well with the public and to be able to assist in several different areas.

Apply on line at skiatookschools.org or mail resume to Skiatook Public Schools, 355 S Osage, Skiatook, OK 74070, Attn: Dr. Missy Bush, Assistant Superintendent.

Return to Learn Plan-July 2020

Skiatook Public Schools has created this plan to aid in navigating the reestablishment of our school where employees, students, and families feel safe and to reduce the impact of COVID-19 conditions upon returning to the district.

The guidelines referenced in this plan are based on guidance from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and State and County Health Departments. Regular updates will be made to this plan based on information provided by the CDC and applicable federal, state and local agencies.

Please follow the link below for a PDF copy of our plan.

https://bit.ly/2EjN45S

Matthew is planning to attend Arizona State University or OU to major in music education.

We applaud both of these young men for their accomplishments.

post_text: Skiatook Drama and Advanced Placement Literature classes saw a production of Shakespeare's Winter's Tale at Oral Roberts University on September 25. Forty-five students from Skiatook were able to travel to the campus for the free performance provided by ORU. post_text: The Skiatook Board of Education has an opening for Board Position #5. This position will be appointed by the current board members and will finish out the 5 year term of Ka'Lu Underwood. All interested applicants must be a resident of District #5 (see map) and will need to send a letter expressing their interest and a resume to Mike Mullins, Board President. This information can be emailed to, mmullins@skiatookschools.org or mailed to Skiatook Schools, 355 South Osage, Skiatook, OK, 74070, Attn: Mike Mullins. All letters of interest will need to be turned in no later than August 30, 2019.

post_text: Skiatook Debate students made it to the Semifinals of the State Debate Tournament on April 5. Partners Rylee Houston & Joey Breckon ended in the final four of the state tournament losing the state championship to private school rival Crossing Christian. The placing left Skiatook as the highest ranked public school in Oklahoma. Other Skiatook Debate teams appearing at the state contest included partners Dakota Teel and Madi Perigo who ended the year ranked 11th in the state and partners Janessa Spencer and Kyra Edgerton who ended ranked 13th in the state. This is the ninth time that Skiatook has reached the state semifinals in the last dozen years.

post_text:
Students from the Skiatook High School Vocal Music Program participated in the OSSAA District Solo and Ensemble contest on February 23. Matt Cox, Kathryn George, Kacie Anderson, Mason Hopper, Mattie Parker, Kelsi Campbell, Zack Prater, Abrianna DeLeon, and Kize Brayden received superior ratings in vocal solo performance. Also, Lizzie Garrison received an excellent rating in solo vocal performance.

Kize Brayden and Mason Hopper received a superior rating for vocal duet, as did Mattie Parker and Kelsi Campbell.

The HS Women's Ensemble, consisting of Kelsi Campbell, Mattie Parker, Emi Szabo, Holly Harris, McKay Schnoebelen, Kacie Anderson, Kathryn George, Olivia Anderson, and Abrianna DeLeon, received a superior rating in ensemble performance.

The individuals and ensembles that received a superior rating will be going on to compete at the state level in April.

It was a great weekend for vocal music at SHS! Thanks to you for all of the support!

Skiatook High School is proud to recognize Kacie Anderson and Madeline Parker as our top academic students of the Class of 2019.

Kacie has been named Valedictorian of the class. She has earned a 4.345 GPA and plans to attend Brigham Young University to major in mathematics.

Madeline has been named Salutatorian of the class. She has earned a 4.343 GPA and is considering attending Rogers State University, Northeastern State University, or the University of Tulsa. She plans to major in criminal justice.

We are proud of both of these ladies and their accomplishments.

post_text: Mattie Parker, a senior at Skiatook High School will perform in Kansas City, Mo. in February as part of the American Choral Directors Association National Honor Choir. To be selected as part of the honor choir, Mattie auditioned against students from all over the country. Being chosen for the National Honor choir ranks Mattie as one of the best singers in the country. The choir will perform at the ACDA National Convention. These singers will rehearse with master conductor, Sandra Snow, and perform music at the very highest level. Mattie is the daughter of Will and Missy Parker. She is under the instruction of Skiatook High School choral director Taylor Conley, assistant Robin Edens, and Amanda Foyle of Foyle Music Studio of Owasso.

Due to increasing unsafe behaviors and littering on Skiatook High School campus after hours, our board of education has approved and given authority to Skiatook Police Department to issue written warnings and tickets for trespassing.

Students congregating in the school parking lot or other campus locations after school hours risk being issued a ticket. This does not pertain to students attending evening school activities or events.

We encourage all students to adhere to this notice and avoid possible law enforcement intervention.

Skiatook High School's Marching Bulldog Band performed at the Ozarko Marching Band Festival Contest held at Missouri State in Springfield, Missouri, Saturday, October 6.

Skiatook was one of 23 bands that performed during the preliminary round. In its division, Skiatook received an award for Best Music and a 3rd place finish.

The band was also asked to perform in the final round.

Due to weather, the final round was stopped before the last bands could perform, so no further awards were given.

Seven Skiatook students qualified for the state debate and speech contest at the regional contest at Bixby on March 9-10.

Team debate students qualifying included: Joey Breckon & Dalton Thompson, Austyn Potter & Rylee Houston, and
Maverick Williams & Kyra Edgerton. Kaylee Aber qualified for state in US current events speaking.

Other regional performers included: Jewel Santini, Kaitlyn Loveless, Bailey Gilmore, Jessica Giles, Lizzy Doughtery, Alex Ragsdale. Other speech or debate regional presenters included Geoffery Thompson, Christian Johnston, Madi Perigo, and Bethany Slatcher.

Volunteer judging at the regional was provided by team alumni: Heather Branaman, Sam Branaman, Kathryn Adams, Jerica Wilson, Baylee Stumpf, and Zach LeClair.

The State Tournament is scheduled at the University of Oklahoma on April 4-7.

The Skiatook High School and Newman Middle School archery teams competed at the Oklahoma NASP East Region, Tier 2 State Tournament in Tulsa on February 21, 2016.

The Skiatook High School team finished in 8th place out of 26 schools. Male high scorer was Tyler Bingamon, and female high scorer was Greyce Seifried. Several archers achieved personal best scores. This team competed with two substitute archers; their sponsors are pleased with their results!

The Newman Middle School took five archers to compete, which is seven fewer than a full team. Male high scorer was Hayden Baker and female high scorer was Abby Decker. Many archers also achieved personal best scores. For such a small team, these students did well!

It was an excellent effort all around by the communities in Broken Arrow, Collinsville, Skiatook, and Tulsa – but the City of Skiatook won the day with 33.93% of its youth [ages 0-17] registering in the 2017 Summer Reading Program.

City of Broken Arrow | 24.06%
City of Collinsville | 33.51%
City of Skiatook | 33.93%
City of Tulsa | 19.64%

These were the results from our Summer Reading Program! Mrs. Wyckoff deserves an applause from us and the Skiatook School System for all the wonderful work she did helping us set up visits for the 5th grade in May.

Cones and barriers have been placed in the parking lot to create a road in front of the construction fencing. Students must park on the north end of the student lot or in the student senior parking lot. Students do not have to be a senior to park in the senior parking lot. No parking is available near the construction fencing or in front of BWAC. We will have school staff directing drivers tomorrow morning. Please pay special attention to the boundaries in the parking lot. Drivers should be cautious and drive safely through the area.

Congratulations to Chase Davis for placing 2nd at the National Association of Teachers of Singing. This means he is considered one of the 2 top singers in the state. Chase has also received a very large scholarship to OBU.
Congratulations to Bailey Stumpf and Chase Davis for being selected to receive the State Superintendent's Arts Award.

post_text: Skiatook Public Schools is excited to announce that we are offering full day Pre-K for the 2017-18 school year. We will no longer offer our half day Pre-K program. Students will be placed according to a first come, first served basis. Pre-K and Kindergarten Round Up Enrollment Night will be April 27th from 5:30-7:00 pm at Marrs Elementary. For more information, please visit www.skiatookschools.org/schools/marrs-elementary/all-day-pre-k-information/
shared_text:
SKIATOOKSCHOOLS.ORG
All day Pre-K Information – Skiatook Public Schools
text:
Skiatook Public Schools is excited to announce that we are offering full day Pre-K for the 2017-18 school year. We will no longer offer our half day Pre-K program. Students will be placed according to a first come, first served basis. Pre-K and Kindergarten Round Up Enrollment Night will be April 27th from 5:30-7:00 pm at Marrs Elementary. For more information, please visit www.skiatookschools.org/schools/marrs-elementary/all-day-pre-k-information/
